  "What is the standard form equation of a circle with center (2, 3) and radius 5?": "",
  "(x + 2)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 25": "",
  "(x - 2)^2 - (y - 3)^2 = 25": "",
  "(x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 5": "",
  "(x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 25": "",
  "The standard form of a circle is (x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2, where (h, k) is the center and r is the radius. With center (2, 3) and r = 5: (x - 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 25.": "",
  "Which conic section is represented by x^2/16 + y^2/9 = 1?": "",
  "Parabola": "",
  "Ellipse": "",
  "Hyperbola": "",
  "Circle": "",
  "The equation x^2/16 + y^2/9 = 1 is in the standard form of an ellipse (x^2/a^2 + y^2/b^2 = 1) with a = 4 and b = 3. The plus sign and different denominators indicate an ellipse.": "",
  "What is the vertex of the parabola y = (x - 1)^2 + 4?": "",
  "(4, 1)": "",
  "(-1, 4)": "",
  "(1, -4)": "",
  "(1, 4)": "",
  "In vertex form y = a(x - h)^2 + k, the vertex is (h, k). Here h = 1 and k = 4, so the vertex is (1, 4).": "",
  "Which conic section is represented by x^2/9 - y^2/4 = 1?": "",
  "The minus sign between the squared terms and the equals-1 form indicate a hyperbola: x^2/a^2 - y^2/b^2 = 1. This hyperbola opens left and right with a = 3 and b = 2.": "",
  "For the ellipse x^2/25 + y^2/9 = 1, what is the length of the major axis?": "",
  "25": "",
  "10": "",
  "5": "",
  "3": "",
  "The larger denominator is 25, so a^2 = 25 and a = 5. The major axis length is 2a = 10. The major axis runs along the x-axis since a^2 is under x^2.": "",
  "What is the focus of the parabola y = x^2/(4p) when p = 2 and the vertex is at the origin?": "",
  "(0, -2)": "",
  "(0, 4)": "",
  "(0, 2)": "",
  "(2, 0)": "",
  "For a vertical parabola x^2 = 4py with vertex at the origin, the focus is at (0, p). With p = 2, the focus is at (0, 2), which is 2 units above the vertex.": "",
  "What are the asymptotes of the hyperbola x^2/16 - y^2/9 = 1?": "",
  "y = +/- 3x": "",
  "y = +/- (4/3)x": "",
  "y = +/- (3/4)x": "",
  "y = +/- 4x": "",
  "For x^2/a^2 - y^2/b^2 = 1, the asymptotes are y = +/- (b/a)x. Here a = 4 and b = 3, so the asymptotes are y = +/- (3/4)x.": "",
  "Identify the center and radius: x^2 + y^2 - 6x + 4y - 12 = 0.": "",
  "Center (3, -2), radius 5": "",
  "Center (6, -4), radius 12": "",
  "Center (-3, 2), radius 5": "",
  "Center (3, -2), radius 25": "",
  "Complete the square: (x^2 - 6x + 9) + (y^2 + 4y + 4) = 12 + 9 + 4 = 25. So (x - 3)^2 + (y + 2)^2 = 25. Center is (3, -2) and radius is sqrt(25) = 5.": "",
  "For the ellipse x^2/25 + y^2/16 = 1, what is the distance from the center to each focus?": "",
  "4": "",
  "9": "",
  "For an ellipse, c^2 = a^2 - b^2 = 25 - 16 = 9, so c = 3. The foci are at (+/-3, 0), each 3 units from the center.": "",
  "Which conic section does the general equation x^2 + y^2 + 6x - 2y + 1 = 0 represent?": "",
  "Both x^2 and y^2 have the same coefficient (1) and the same sign, which indicates a circle. Completing the square: (x+3)^2 + (y-1)^2 = 9. Center (-3, 1), radius 3.": "",
  "What is a conic section?": "",
  "A curve obtained by intersecting a cone with a plane at various angles": "",
  "A section of the coordinate plane divided by axes": "",
  "Any curved line on a graph": "",
  "A three-dimensional shape": "",
  "Conic sections are curves formed by the intersection of a plane with a double-napped cone. Depending on the angle of intersection, the result is a circle, ellipse, parabola, or hyperbola.": "",
  "What is an ellipse?": "",
  "The set of all points equidistant from a point and a line": "",
  "The set of all points where the sum of distances to two fixed points (foci) is constant": "",
  "The set of all points where the difference of distances to two foci is constant": "",
  "The set of all points equidistant from a center point": "",
  "An ellipse is defined as the set of all points in a plane such that the sum of the distances from any point on the ellipse to two fixed points (foci) is a constant equal to 2a.": "",
  "What is a hyperbola?": "",
  "The graph of a quadratic function": "",
  "The set of all points where the absolute difference of distances to two fixed points (foci) is constant": "",
  "A curve that forms a complete closed loop": "",
  "The set of all points where the sum of distances to two foci is constant": "",
  "A hyperbola is the set of all points where the absolute difference of distances from any point to two fixed foci equals a constant (2a). Unlike an ellipse, a hyperbola has two separate branches.": "",
  "What is the focus of a parabola?": "",
  "The vertex of the parabola, particularly regarding directrix when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The center of the parabola, particularly regarding that under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The highest point on the parabola, particularly regarding units within the typical range of values": "",
  "A fixed point inside the parabola such that every point on the parabola is equidistant from the focus and the directrix": "",
  "The focus is a fixed point such that any point on the parabola is equidistant from the focus and the directrix (a fixed line). The focus lies on the axis of symmetry, p units from the vertex.": "",
  "What is the directrix of a parabola?": "",
  "A fixed line such that every point on the parabola is equidistant from the directrix and the focus": "",
  "The x-axis, particularly regarding units under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The tangent line at the vertex when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "The axis of symmetry, particularly regarding fixed as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The directrix is a fixed line perpendicular to the axis of symmetry, located p units from the vertex on the side opposite the focus. Together with the focus, it defines the parabola.": "",
  "What does 'eccentricity' mean for a conic section?": "",
  "The distance between the foci": "",
  "The radius of the conic": "",
  "The area enclosed by the conic": "",
  "A number that describes how much the conic deviates from being circular": "",
  "Eccentricity (e) measures how much a conic deviates from a circle. For a circle e = 0, for an ellipse 0 < e < 1, for a parabola e = 1, and for a hyperbola e > 1.": "",
  "What does 'major axis' mean for an ellipse?": "",
  "The circumference of the ellipse": "",
  "The shortest diameter of the ellipse": "",
  "The longest diameter of the ellipse, passing through both foci and the center": "",
  "The major axis is the longest line segment through the center of the ellipse, connecting the two vertices. Its length is 2a, where a is the semi-major axis. The foci lie along the major axis.": "",
  "What does 'completing the square' mean in the context of conic sections?": "",
  "Drawing a square around the conic": "",
  "Squaring both sides of an equation": "",
  "Finding the square root of the equation": "",
  "An algebraic technique to rewrite a conic equation from general form into standard form": "",
  "Completing the square is an algebraic technique used to convert a conic's general form (Ax^2 + Bxy + Cy^2 + Dx + Ey + F = 0) into standard form, which reveals the center, radii, and other key features.": "",
  "What are 'vertices' of a hyperbola?": "",
  "The endpoints of the asymptotes": "",
  "The points where the asymptotes cross the axes": "",
  "The two points where the hyperbola intersects its transverse axis, closest to the center": "",
  "The two foci of the hyperbola": "",
  "The vertices of a hyperbola are the two points where the curve intersects the transverse axis (the axis passing through the foci). They are the closest points on the hyperbola to its center.": "",
  "What does 'asymptote' mean in the context of a hyperbola?": "",
  "A tangent line to the hyperbola": "",
  "The axis of symmetry": "",
  "A line that the branches of the hyperbola approach but never reach": "",
  "A line connecting the two vertices": "",
  "Asymptotes are lines that the branches of a hyperbola approach as they extend to infinity. For x^2/a^2 - y^2/b^2 = 1, the asymptotes are y = +/-(b/a)x. They form a guide box for sketching.": "",
  "A satellite orbits Earth in an elliptical path. The closest distance to Earth's center is 7,000 km and the farthest is 13,000 km. What is the semi-major axis of the orbit?": "",
  "7,000 km": "",
  "13,000 km": "",
  "20,000 km": "",
  "10,000 km": "",
  "The semi-major axis a = (closest + farthest) / 2 = (7000 + 13000) / 2 = 20000 / 2 = 10,000 km. This is the average of the minimum and maximum distances.": "",
  "A spotlight shines against a flat wall, creating a circular patch of light. If the equation of the circle is (x - 5)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 16, what is the diameter of the lit area?": "",
  "32 units": "",
  "8 units": "",
  "16 units": "",
  "4 units": "",
  "The radius r = sqrt(16) = 4 units. The diameter is 2r = 8 units. The center of the lit patch is at (5, 3) on the wall.": "",
  "A bridge has a parabolic arch that spans 40 meters and reaches a maximum height of 10 meters. If the vertex is at the top, write the equation of the arch with the vertex at the origin. What is the value of p?": "",
  "p = -40": "",
  "p = -10": "",
  "p = 20": "",
  "p = 10": "",
  "With vertex at origin opening downward: x^2 = 4py. The arch passes through (20, -10) since half-span is 20 m and it drops 10 m. So 400 = 4p(-10) = -40p, giving p = -10.": "",
  "A whispering gallery is in the shape of an ellipse where the foci are 30 feet apart and the major axis is 50 feet long. What is the length of the minor axis?": "",
  "20 feet": "",
  "40 feet": "",
  "30 feet": "",
  "25 feet": "",
  "a = 25 (half of 50), c = 15 (half of 30). b^2 = a^2 - c^2 = 625 - 225 = 400, so b = 20. The minor axis length is 2b = 40 feet.": "",
  "A cooling tower at a power plant has a hyperbolic cross-section given by x^2/400 - y^2/900 = 1 (in meters). What is the minimum width of the tower?": "",
  "30 meters": "",
  "60 meters": "",
  "40 meters": "",
  "20 meters": "",
  "The minimum width occurs at the vertices where y = 0: x^2/400 = 1, so x = +/-20. The minimum width is the distance between vertices = 2(20) = 40 meters.": "",
  "A satellite dish is parabolic with the receiver at the focus. If the dish is 4 meters wide and 1 meter deep, where should the receiver be placed (how far from the vertex)?": "",
  "1 meter": "",
  "2 meters": "",
  "4 meters": "",
  "0.5 meters": "",
  "Using x^2 = 4py with the point (2, 1) on the parabola (half-width = 2, depth = 1): 4 = 4p(1), so p = 1. The receiver should be 1 meter from the vertex.": "",
  "An elliptical running track has a semi-major axis of 100 meters and a semi-minor axis of 60 meters. What is the approximate perimeter of the track? Use the approximation P ≈ pi * [3(a+b) - sqrt((3a+b)(a+3b))].": "",
  "Approximately 400 meters": "",
  "Approximately 509 meters": "",
  "Approximately 628 meters": "",
  "Approximately 320 meters": "",
  "Using the Ramanujan approximation: P ≈ pi[3(100+60) - sqrt((300+60)(100+180))] = pi[480 - sqrt(360*280)] = pi[480 - sqrt(100800)] = pi[480 - 317.5] ≈ pi * 162.5 ≈ 510.5, approximately 509 meters.": "",
  "Two radio stations are 200 miles apart. A ship determines it is 40 miles closer to station A than to station B. The ship lies on a hyperbola with the stations as foci. What is the value of a for this hyperbola?": "",
  "20": "",
  "100": "",
  "80": "",
  "40": "",
  "For a hyperbola, the difference of distances to the foci equals 2a. Since the ship is 40 miles closer to A: |d_B - d_A| = 40 = 2a, so a = 20.": "",
  "A tunnel entrance has a semi-elliptical shape 20 feet wide at the base and 8 feet tall at the center. Can a truck that is 10 feet wide and 7 feet tall drive through the tunnel?": "",
